<DOC><DOCNO> AP890815-0210 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 0121EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-15 0829</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0867</SECOND><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   UAL Corp.'s stock price kept rising amidunconfirmed reports that several suitors have expressed interest inbuying the airline company.   UAL rose $1.50 to close at $258.50 a share Monday in New YorkStock Exchange trading. The increase followed a gain of about 56percent last week following a $240-a-share takeover proposal to UAL,parent of United Airlines, from Los Angeles investor Marvin Davis.   The New York leveraged buyout firms Kohlberg Kravis Roberts andamp; Coand Forstmann Little andamp; Co. also reportedly have expressed interestto UAL officials in buying the Chicago-based company, whileofficials of New York-based Pan Am Corp. have stated they wereinterested in a possible merger.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Business inventories rose 0.4 percent in Juneas business sales fell 0.3 percent, the government said. Analystssaid the report indicated slow but continued economic growth withlow inflation.   Inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth asproduction exceeds demand, a process that sometimes leads to a lossof jobs as businesses cut their output. Economists, however, saidthe inventories reported Monday are not unusually large inproportion to sales.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Construction of houses, apartments andcondominiums fell 8 percent in the second quarter to the lowest ratein more than six years, said the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-HillInformation Services Co.   Residential starts during the year's second three months totaled388,926 units, down from 420,843 units during the same period a yearearlier, the business research company said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush selected White House aideRichard C. Breeden, an attorney and banking specialist, to bechairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission.   Breeden, 39, has served in a variety of capacities under Bush,most recently as White House point man on the savings-and-loanrestructuring legislation. The SEC nomination, announced Monday,requires Senate confirmation.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former trader in the Chicago MercantileExchange's yen futures pit became the 13th futures trader to pleadinnocent to charges stemming from the federal probe of suspectedfraud in the world's largest futures markets.   Michael Sidel, 42, of suburban Lake Forest, stood silently beforeU.S. District Judge George M. Marovich as his lawyer entered theplea Monday.   Sidel, accused of defrauding his customers at the ChicagoMercantile Exchange, is charged with one count of violating theCommodities Exchange Act and one count of mail fraud.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush signed legislation that willspeed $897 million in assistance to farmers whose crops he said hadbeen battered this year by ``the forces of nature.''   The bulk of the aid _ $400 million _ will go to wheat farmerswhose winter harvest in Kansas and other states was devastated bydrought.   At the other extreme, the Disaster Assistance Act signed Mondaywill compensate farmers in the South and elsewhere whose rice,soybean, cotton and other crops were wiped out by rain, wind andfloods.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastman Kodak Co. Chairman Colby Chandler testifiedhe knew getting into instant photography could mean a lawsuit fromcompetitor Polaroid Corp. but said he was convinced his companywould win.   Chandler was called to testify Monday in a U.S. District Courttrial to determine how many dollars in damages his company will haveto pay Polaroid. An earlier federal court decision established thatKodak infringed on patents of Polaroid, the Cambridge, Mass.-basedpioneer of instant photography.   Polaroid is seeking nearly $12 billion, while Kodak has argued itshould pay $177 million.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has agreed to pay$975,000 in fines to 10 states in an effort to clear its name andoperate freely around the country despite a guilty plea to federalsecurities crimes, officials said.   Drexel said Monday it expects to pay $11.5 million overall tosettle with the states, avoid litigation and retain its ability todo business, but some states still want to revoke the New Yorkinvestment firm's brokerage licenses, according to securitiesregulators.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Teachers and school administrators got theirfirst look at Turner Broadcasting System Inc.'s daily news show foruse in the classroom, a commercial-free alternative to the sponsorednews program that Whittle Communications plans to launch next spring.   The first program of CNN Newsroom was carried early Monday onCable News Network. Teachers are being encourged to record the showand use it in the classroom to help augment their course plans.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stocks retreated further in quiet trading Monday from near-recordlevels reached last week, as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrialsfell 6.07 points to 2,677.92.   Bond prices plummeted in a second straight selloff.   The dollar finished higher against major foreign currencies inbrisk trading, extending last week's strong rally.   Copper prices surged, grain and soybean prices dropped, energyfutures were mostly lower, precious metals rose modestly, and meatand pork futures fell.</TEXT></DOC>